{
  "profile_id": "client-resistance-chasing-unavailable-001",
  "coach_config_id": "coach-v4-graph-walk",
  "turns": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "Okay so — *[laughs a little, settling in]* — I keep falling for emotionally unavailable people. Like, it's basically a curse at this point. Third relationship, same exact configuration, and I'm sitting here going... *why do I always end up with people who just cannot show up?*"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "That laugh at the end of \"why do I always end up with people who just cannot show up\" — what's underneath it?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*[pauses, slightly caught off guard, then recovers with a smile]*\n\nOh, it's just — I mean, it's kind of absurd, right? Like at some point you have to laugh at yourself. Three times! The same thing! It's almost impressive.\n\n*[waves a hand]*\n\nBut underneath it... I don't know, frustration, I guess. Like genuine frustration that I keep doing this to myself. Or — that this keeps *happening.* You know what I mean."
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "I noticed the switch there — \"doing this to myself\" and then \"this keeps happening.\"\n\nWhich one is actually true for you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*[slight eye roll, but caught it herself]*\n\nI mean — both? Neither? \n\n*[shifts in seat]*\n\nLook, I know what you're angling at. And I've done enough therapy to know the \"you're the common denominator\" thing. I get it intellectually. But like — I was *there.* I was the one texting first, I was the one planning things, I was the one saying \"can we talk about where this is going\" and getting... *[does a vague, dismissive gesture]* ...nothing. Emotional fog. So if I'm \"doing this to myself,\" what exactly am I doing? Because from where I'm standing I was the available one."
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "You were the available one — and you kept choosing people who weren't.\n\nWhat's that about?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*[laughs, a little sharp]*\n\nOkay, so now we're doing the \"why do you pick unavailable people\" thing. Which, I have asked myself this question approximately four hundred times. \n\n*[leans forward slightly, almost performative now]*\n\nAnd I have theories! I have so many theories. Attachment stuff, father stuff — my dad was not exactly an open book emotionally, shocker — I've read the books, I've done the journaling. And I still end up here. So clearly the intellectual understanding is not the thing that fixes it.\n\n*[sits back]*\n\nBut I also want to push back a little, because it's not like I'm scanning a room going \"ooh, that one looks emotionally unavailable, perfect.\" They seem great at first. They seem warm and interested. And then slowly the distance appears, and by then I'm already... *[trails off]* ...in it."
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "What's it like when the distance appears?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 9,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*[something shifts briefly in her face, then smooths over]*\n\nIt's — honestly? It's activating. Like, suddenly I'm on high alert. I'm reading every text, I'm trying to figure out what changed, I'm working *harder.* \n\n*[small laugh]*\n\nWhich I realize even as I say it sounds kind of — I don't know. Like a hamster wheel. But in the moment it doesn't feel like that. In the moment it feels like... solving something. Like if I can just figure out the right thing to say or do, I can get back to how it was at the beginning.\n\n*[pause]*\n\nAnd sometimes it works, actually. Like sometimes I'd crack through and there'd be this moment of real connection and it would feel — \n\n*[stops herself]*\n\n...really good. And then it would close back up again."
    },
    {
      "turn": 10,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "That moment when you crack through — what does it feel like?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 11,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*[goes a little still, then fills the space quickly]*\n\nIt feels like — winning, kind of? Like you worked for something and you got it. There's this rush of like, *see, I knew it was there, I knew they were capable of it.*\n\n*[tilts head, almost analytical now]*\n\nIt's probably dopamine, right? Like the variable reward schedule thing. I know about this. The intermittent reinforcement makes the connection feel more valuable than it actually is because you had to work for it.\n\n*[gestures vaguely]*\n\nSo I know the mechanism. I just apparently haven't figured out how to... want something different."
    },
    {
      "turn": 12,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "You just moved pretty fast from \"winning\" into the neuroscience.\n\nWhat was happening right before you did that?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 13,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*[opens mouth, closes it]*\n\n*[small laugh, slightly defensive]*\n\nI mean — I was answering your question?\n\n*[pause, longer this time]*\n\n...Okay. Yeah. I felt something and then I explained it. That's — yeah, that's a thing I do.\n\n*[quieter, less performative]*\n\nIt felt like... relief, I think. Those moments. Like something that had been clenched just — loosened a little. And then I turned it into a TED talk because that's easier than sitting in the relief part.\n\n*[looks at coach, slightly wary]*\n\nWhere are you going with this?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 14,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "I'm not going anywhere.\n\nWhat happens if you just sit in the relief part for a second?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 15,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*[looks at the coach for a moment, something flickering across her face]*\n\n*[quiet laugh, self-deprecating]*\n\nGod, you're annoying.\n\n*[but she does pause. actually pauses. fidgets slightly with her sleeve]*\n\nIt's... \n\n*[longer silence than she's comfortable with]*\n\nIt's like — okay, it's like standing in a doorway. Like the relief is there but I'm not fully in it. I'm kind of... hovering at the edge of it.\n\n*[blinks, refocuses, and the analytical layer starts coming back up]*\n\nI think it's because the relief was always temporary, so my body learned not to fully — \n\n*[catches herself]*\n\nI'm doing it again, aren't I."
    }
  ],
